column168: I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST THAT THIS SPILLED PACKAGE WAS AT THE STATION.  THIS ORIGINALLY SPILLED ON 8-6-97 BUT WAS NOT PHONED IN TO THIS OFFICE.  UPON INSPECTION ON 9-5-97 IT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE SEAM.  INSIDE WAS A PRODUCT CALLED REGENCY PROFESSIONAL DUST MOP TREATMENT, DM-555. THESE WERE METAL AEROSOL CANS.  AS THIS FALLS UNDER THE DEFINITION OF DANGEROUS GOODS UNDER IATA REGULATIONS (AS EITHER A NON-FLAMMABLE GAS OR SOMETIMES A FLAMMABLE GAS DEPENDING UPON THE FLASH POINT, IT WAS DETERMINED UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOOD AT THAT TIME.  THE STATION IS HOLDING THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  I PHONED FAA AGENT ON CALL KEITH HUNTER AT 404-305-6862 ON 9//5 AT 7:55 PM TO REPORT THIS. ALEX EVANS FROM THE LOCAL OFFICE CALLED ON TUESDAY TO SAY HE WOULD BE INVESTIGATING THIS UNDECLARED.

I WAS LOADING CRUDE OIL FROM A TANK BATTERY INTO A TANK TRK. NORMAL PROCEDURE  IS TO LOAD UNTIL ON SIDE OF TRUCK REGISTERS 90%.  GAUGE ON TRUCK STOPPED AT 855.  BY THE TIME I REALIZED GAUGE WASN'T WORKING, TRAILER WAS FULL AND STARTED TO VENT CRUDE OIL AT THE REAR OF TRAILER I IMMEDIATELY SHUT  OFF  VALVES TO STOP FLOW. SPILL WAS ON DRIVE WAY TO LEASE SITE SURROUNDED BY COTTLE PASTURE.  PUMPER WAS PRESENT AND WE COVERED SPILL WITH DIRT TO PREVENT CATTLE HAVING ACCESS TO IT  AS PER HIS INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING PRODUCT INTO UNDERGROUND TANK AND THOUGHT THAT THE DELIVERY WAS FINISHED.  BEFORE DISCONNECTING THE DELIVERY HOSES, THE DRIVER ENTERED THE STATION OFFICE TO DROP OFF THE PAPERWORK.  WHILE DOING THIS , GAS BACKED UP IN THE DELIVERY HOSE, WHICH WAS NOT EMPTY, DUE TO A MALFUNCTION OF THE OVERFILL PROTECTION MECHANISM ON THE UNDERGROUND TANK, AND SEEPED FROM THE DELIVERY FITTING. SPILL CLEAN UP CONTRACTORS WERE ALSO CALLED,  AND PICKED UP THE ABSORBENT AND CLEANED THE STORM SEWERS IN THE AREA.  THEY ALSO PLACED A SORBENT BOOM ON A NEAR BY UNNAMED CREEK, BUT NO PRODUCT APPEARED TO MAKE IT INTO THE CREEK.

STC UNIT WAS STOPPED AT A WEIGH STATION ON I-10 EAST IN TOOMEY, LA. A LEAKING PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS IDENTIFIED.  THE DEVICE WAS ALLOWING VAPORS TO BE RELEASED.  THE PRESSURE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE UNIT WAS RELEASED BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.  AFTER LOADING, THE UNIT WAS INSPECTED BY STC MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL AND SEEMED TO BE IN GOOD REPAIR.

THE TANKER'S VALVE SEAT WAS WORN.  THE DRIVER LOADED AN ACID RINSE WATER INTO THE TANKER AND GRIT LODGED IN THE ENDCAP WHICH CAUSED THE ENDCAP TO FAIL.  THERE WAS A DAMP AREA UNDER THE LEAKING ENDCAP.  ALL OF THE DAMP STONES AND GRAVEL WERE REMOVED (1 - 55 GAL DRUM).  PLACED IN A DRUM AND DISPOSED OF AT A PERMITTED TREATMENT/DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE VALVE WAS REPLACED ON THE TANKER.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST LOADED AND WAS LEAVING INMAN VIA I-26.  DRIVER ENTERED ON RAMP AT EXIT 17 AND WHILE TRAVELING DOWN RAMP, REACHED DOWN TO THE FLOOR TO RETREIVE AN ITEM HE HAD DROPPED.  AT THAT TIME VEHICLE RAN OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. IN AN ATTEMPT TO STEER BACK INTO ROADWAY, DRIVER OVERCORRECTED AND JERKED TRACTOR BACK ONTO PAVEMENT. TANK TURNED OVER AT THAT POINT.  THE TRACTOR REMAINED UPRIGHT. UPON NOTIFICATION, WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WHO ARRIVED ONSITE BEFORE WE DID. THEY IMPLEMENTED MEASURES TO DAM UP THE SPILLED LIQUID AND THEN INSTITUTED MEASURES TO REMOVE THE LIQUID FROM THE SURFACE OF THE GROUND.  OBVIOUSLY, DRIVER SHOULD HAVE NEVER TAKEN HIS EYES OFF OF THE ROAD; ADDITIONALLY, HAD HIS SPEED BEEN LESS, HE MAY HAVE BEEN ABLE TO RETURN BOTH TRACTOR AND TANK TO THE ROADWAY.  IT HAS BEEN REITERATED TO THE DRIVERS THE ABSOLUTE NECESSITY OF THEIR GIVING THE ROAD 100% OF THEIR ATTENTION. THE ENTIRE INCIDENT HAS BEEN REVIEWED WITH ALL DRIVERS, AND WE HAVE DISCUSSED THE THINGS DONE WRONG AND WHAT COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE ACCIDENT.

column168: WHILE LOADING DRUMS THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT. CONTENTS STARTED LEAKING AND HAD A VERY BAD ODOR. THE TRAILER WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE DOCK WHERE THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND IT STOPPED LEAKING. OIL DRY WAS APPLIED ON THE CONTENTS LEAKED. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS AIRED OUT THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

THE UNITS WERE OFF LOADED AT DENVER TERMINAL. A SULFUR LIKE SMELL WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE UNITS WERE INSPECTED AND NO LEAKS WERE FOUND. THE UNIT WAS MOVED OUTSIDE TO LET THEM BREATHE. THE BILL WAS NOTICED AND THOUGHT THE TRAILER WERE EMPTY. THE TANKS REACTED TO HEAT AND MORE VAPORS WENT INTO THE AIR. NEIGHBORS COMPLAINED OF GAS LEAK AND PUBLIC SERVICE WAS IN THE AREA AND CHECKED OUT THE UNIT. FIREMEN WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND THE END RESULT WAS FIREMEN CLOSED THE LEAKING VALVE BY APPLYING SILICON SEALANT TYPE SEALER AND OK'ED FOR TRANSPORT.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL SWITCH CREW NOTICED VAPOR FUMES COMING FROM AROUND THE CENTER OF TANK CAR RCRX001097. CAR WAS ISOLATED. CHEMTREC, MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT AND FERGUSON-HARBOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CALLED. RESPONSE TEAM FOUND ONE BROKEN BOLT ON THE MANWAY COVER. ILLINOIS CENTRAL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT MADE TEMPORARY REPAIR TO BOLT AND RESPONSE TEAM PUT BOLT ON TO STOP LEAK. CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO THE TRASH TRACK AND WILL BE HELD UNTIL SHIPPER SENDS NEW BOLT FOR PERMANENT REPAIR TO CAR. EMPLOYEE CLAIMS HE INHALED HYDROCHLORIC ACID FUMES AT GROUND LEVEL NEAR THE CAR. SUPERVISOR TOOK EMPLOYEE TO HOSPITAL TO BE EXAMINED, DOCTORS COULD FIND NOTHING WRONG WITH EMPLOYEE AND RELEASED HIM TO GO BACK TO WORK.

column168: AS THE DRIVER MADE HIS WAY INTO THE FACILITY, HE NOTICED ACID DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER. HE GOT ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED THEM TO SOAK UP THE ACID. HE THEN NOTIFIED LITTON EMPLOYEES WHO HELPED TO FIND THE PUNCTURED DRUM. UPON FINDING THE PUNCTURED DRUM, THEY PUT IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM CONTAINING THE SPILL. THEY THEN PLACED SODA ASH AND LIME ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.

THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER'S LOCATION. THEN WENT TO THE RESTROOM. WHEN HE RETURNED HE FOUND THE RECEIVER HOLDING HIS FINGER OVER A HOLE IN THE DRUM AND WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE SPREADING ABSORBING MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE RECEIVER PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH A DRUM PICKER ON THE FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON LEAKED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, OF WHICH APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ. RAN OFF TRAILER ONTO MACADAM. THE SPOT THE MACADAM WAS ALSO ABSORBED WITH MATERIAL AND CLEAN UP. IT WAS NOT ENOUGH TO FLOW ANYWHERE.
DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE THE STRUCK B/4 LOADING ON COMET TRAILER 1214. CARBOARD BOXES OF FRT AROUND THE DRUM ON THIS IS OIL SOAKED.

I WAS DELIVERING 2000 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL AT CROUSE FORD. I HEARD THE SOUND OF AIR LEAKING. WHILE SEARCHING FOR THE CAUSE OF THE AIR LEAK, I NOTICED THE FRONT OF THE TANK BUCKLING INWARD. I IMMEDIATELY CEASED PUMPING OPERATIONS. MEANWHILE THE SIDES OF THE TANKS BUCKLED IN AND KEPT INCREASING INWARDS. I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE DISPATCH OFFICE, FOR ASSISTANCE. THEN I NOTICED THE TANK HAP POPPED BACK OUT AND OIL STARTED LEAKING FROM TWO SPOTS IN THE FRONT WALL OF THE TANK. I IMMEDIATELY SET UP A CONTAINMENT BARRIER AND ATTEMPTED TO PLUG THE LEAKS. I WAS ABLE TO STOP ONE LEAK AND HELD MY FINGER ON THE OTHER UNTIL ASSISTANCE ARRIVED. ONCE HELP ARRIVED, THE TRUCK WAS PUMPED EMPTY OF OIL AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP.

column168: WHILE TRANSFERRING BAD BLEACH FROM A CUSTOMER'S TANK, WITH A 2 INCH TRANSFER PUMP SUPPLIED BY ALL PURE CHEMICAL CO.  INTO OUR TANKER TRUCK, THE CAM LOCK FITTING ON THE PUMP CAME LOSE AND A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OCCURRED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ENTIRELY ON THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY AND ON CONCRETE.  NO PRODUCT ENTERED WATERWAYS OR SOIL.  THE CUSTOMER NOTIFIED 911 AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE REPORT TO THE FIRE DEPT WAS 100 GL, BUT THE CUSTOMER LATER CONCLUDED THAT THE SPILL WAS ABOUT 80 GL.  THE CAM LOCK FITTING CAME LOOSE DUE TO THE VIBRATION OF THE PUMP.  IN THE FUTURE, THE USE OF A FLANGE INSTEAD OF A CAM LOCK  OR THE USE OF VELCRO STRAPPING OVER THE CAM LOCK TO PREVENT IT FROM VIBRATING LOOSE.

DURING ATTEMPT TO UNLOAD PRODUCT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING LINE WAS CLOGGED. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL HOOKED UP A NITROGEN LINE TO TRY TO UNCLOG THE DISCHARGE LINE. AN ASHLAND CHEMICAL EMPLOYEE DISCONNECTED THE NITROGEN LINE WITHOUT SHUTTING THE SAMPLE VALVE AND PRODUCT SHOT OUT THROUGH SAMPLE LINE AND SPRAYED 2 ASHLAND EMPLOYEES. THE 2 EMPLOYEES WERE TAKENT TO SAFETY SHOWER. BOTH WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. NEITHER EMPLOYEE MISSED WORK DAYS NOR HAVE LASTING INJURIES. THERE WAS NO ENTRY INTO WATERWAYS. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY EMPLOYEES.

DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY PLANT WORKER- ROBERTO-AS TO WHICH STORAGE TANK TO UNLOAD INTO. PLANT WORKER HOOKED PLANT HOSE TO DRIVER HOSE, AND UNLOADING WAS BEGUN. ABOUT 1 MINUTE INTO UNLOADING, PLANT WORKER TOLD DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN, AS THE CONNECTION WAS MADE TO WRONG STORAGE TANK. DRIVER SHUT DOWN, AND THE PLANT WORKER DISCONNECTED THE HOSE WITHOUT CLOSING PLANT VALVE. PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM HOSE ONTO GROUND AND ONTO THE TRUCK DRIVER. TRUCK DRIVER WAS CLEANED UP AND HE PUT ON CLEAN CLOTHING. THERE IS NO PERMANENT INJURY. PRODUCT SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY PLANT EMPLOYEES. NO WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED.
30 GAL DRUM WAS NOT BLOCKED IN PROPERLY. DRUM TURNED OVER DURING TRANSIT. SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTENTS LEAKED OUT ABOUT 2 CUPS. SPILLED CONTENTS CLEANED UP WITHOUT PROBLEM.

DURING THE DRIVE BACK APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER. WE LOST  APPROXIMATELY 80 TO 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. I NOTICED THE BERKELEY FIRE DEPARTMENT OF THE INCIDENT. THE FIRE CHIEF DROVE THE SAME ROUTE OUR DRIVER HAD TRAVELED TO ASSESS THE SPILL. HE DETERMINED THAT THEY WOULD FLUSH THE PAVEMENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF HANLEY ROAD AND FROST AVENUE. AFTER THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED THE FIRE CHIEF DECIDED THIS WAS ALL THAT WOULD BE NECESSARY AND CONSIDERED THE INCIDENT CLOSED.

column168: THIS SPILL WAS RESULT OF SINGLE VEHICLE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT IN WHICH THE DRIVER OF OUR TRUCK WAS THROWN CLEAR OF THE TRACTOR DURING THE ROLLOVER PROCESS, AND WAS FOUND DEAD AT SCENE FROM CAUSES (UNKNOWN AT DATE OF THIS REPORT) BUT NOT AS A RESULT OF CONTACT WITH THE CONTENTS OF TANK TRAILER.  WITNESSES FOLLOWING OUR TRUCK SAW THE VEHICLE SUDDENLY VEER RIGHT AND LEAVE THE HIGHWAY AND ROLLOVER SEVERAL TIMES.  WHEN VEHICLE CAME TO REST, TRACTOR WAS DESTROYED, AND TRAILER SUSTAINED HEAVY DAMAGE AND COULD BE SEEN LEAKING FROM AIR VALVES ON TOP.  FRESNO COUNTY CALLED IN "M & P" ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC TO STOP LEAK AND CLEANUP.  PRODUCT REMAINING IN WRECKED TANKER WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK TRUCK.  THAT PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER. THE PRODUCT WHICH HAD LEAKED INTO SOIL WAS DETERMINED BY CALIFORNIA ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SYSTEM OFFICER TO BE VOLATILE ENOUGH TO BE ALLOWED TO EVAPORATE AT THE SITE WITHOUT SOIL REMOVAL.

I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM DG/SPILL SPECIALIST AT FEDEX AT GAIR REPORTING THIS SPILL. THEY HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE RECIPIENT WHO INDICATED THAT A PACKAGE THAT HAD JUST BEEN DELIVERED BY THE FEDEX COURIER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THEIR FACILITY.  THEY HAD TOLD THE FEDEX DG SPECIALIST THAT IT WAS HIV.  THE STATION THEN ALERTED THE DELIVERY COURIER.  HE WAS FOUND TO HAVE BLOOD ON HIS LEG.  HE ELECTED TO GO TO THE DOCTOR FOR AN EXAMINATION AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  I PHONED THE SHIPPER AND SPOKE WITH TWO INDIVIDUALS THERE, MARK OCHENDSZKO IN THE LAB AND CATHERINE CHAMBERLAIN WHO IS THE SUPERVISOR OVER THE SHIPPING MANAGER WHO WAS UNAVAILABLE THAT DAY. BOTH INDIVIDUALS INDICATED THAT IT WAS INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCES (HIV).  THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT SENT AS DANGEROUS GOODS; IT WAS NOT IN UN6.2 PACKAGING, NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS, AND THERE WAS NOT A SHIPPER DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  I BELIEVE THIS IS TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  I THEN CALLED THE CENTER FOR DISEASE CONTROL AND SPOKE WITH DR. MATHEWS AT (800)232-0124 TO REPORT THIS.  SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE DONE IN THE CAB AREA OF THE FEDEX TRUCK IN CASE ANY BLOOD HAD LEAKED FROM THE COURIER'S LEG AS WELL AS IN THE BACK AND SAID FAA AGENT PAUL KRISBI WOULD BE INVESTIGATING THIS ONE.  LATER FAA AGENT MARK BLAZIE INDICATED HE WOULD BE INVESTIGATING THIS CASE.  THE PACKAGE WILL BE HELD AT THE FEDEX FACILITY PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.
THIS PACKAGE LEAKED IN THE SYSTEM.  AFTER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE COMPLETED IT WAS CONTAINED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION ON TO THE RECIPIENT OR BACK TO THE SHIPPER.
THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED IN OUR SYSTEM.  AFTER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION TO THE RECIPENT OR BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: THE BOX WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION TO THE FEDEX STATION TO BE INSPECTED.  THE CAN HAS A HANDLE THAT WAS ACTUATED, ALLOWING THE GAS TO ESCAPE . column168: ON SEPTEMBER 12 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 1640 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR SERIAL NUMBER ACFX 89859, LOADED WITH METHANOL, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT OUR LATANIER, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE LEAKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY PLACING A TRASH CAN UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE LOUISIANA EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMISSION WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1845 HOURS.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS ALSO IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND SUBSEQUENTLY DISPATCHED RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE.  THE SHIPPER RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE AT APPROX 0145 HOURS AND STOPPED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP.  ALL CLEAN UP AND PRODUCT DISPOSAL WAS HANDLED BY THE SHIPPER.  THE REPAIRED TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION ON SEPTEMBER 13, 1997 AT 0245 HOURS.                       *DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE & LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP

ALL SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK AND TO  A SMALL AREA ON A SWITCH TIE LOCATION BELOW THE TANK CAR.  NO MATERIAL MADE CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO PROVIDE FOR REPAIR AN DECONTAMINATION EFFORTS MERICHEM PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT 1530 HOURS, COMPLETING REPAIRS (LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS AND DECON AT 1600 HOURS.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT. ONE OF ONE FIVE GALLON CONTAINER HAD A LOOSE CAP. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING UPS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

UPON RECEIVING THE MSDS I FOUND THAT THE FLASHPOINT IS 111 - 128 DEGREES F. I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE FAA. THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD AT THE FEDEX STATION PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE SHIPPER (ABE) TOLD ME THAT THIS WAS A FAVOR FOR A CUSTOMER AND THAT HE DID NOT KNOW WHAT THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE WERE.

column168: AT TIME OF ROUTINE STOP AND INSPECTION DRIVER OPENED TRAILER AND DISCOVERED MATERIAL WAS COVERING FLOOR OF TRAILER,.  HE CONTACTED OFFICE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT HE COULD NOT HANDLE SPILL CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP AND AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAD DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  DRIVER CONTAINED SPILL AND WAITED FOR RESPONSE CREW. MATERIAL WAS CLEANUP AND NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE PA EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCY AT 08:22 TO A RON KROSHAR.  HE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND THAT THE CONTRACTOR (REACT) WAS ON SITE.  WE WERE INFORMED THAT SOMEONE WOULD BE DISPATCHED.  ONLY A STATE POLICE OFFICIAL SHOWED UP AT THE SCENE AND LEFT AFTER THE SITUATION WAS NOTED TO BE UNDER CONTROL. DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND DISPOSED OF AT ORIGINAL DESTINATION DISPOSAL FACILITY.

THIS LOAD ARRIVED AT OUR CLINTON, MS FACILITY THE NIGHT BEFORE OFF LOADING. THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE ANY THING THAT NIGHT WHEN HE PERFORMED HIS DAILY INSPECTION. IN THE MORNING THE DRIVER MOVED THE CARGO TANK INTO POSITION AND STARTED OFF LOADING. WHILE OFF LOADING THE TANK HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SEEPING FROM THE REAR CURB SIDE, ABOUT HALF WAY UP THE SIDE OF THE TANK BARREL. THE LEAK WAS VERY SLIGHT AND THE PRODUCT NEVER ACTUALLY DRIPPED TO THE GROUND. THIS PRODUCT TENDS TO SOLIDIFY AND DRY UP AS IT IS EXPOSED TO AIR. THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO OFF LOAD AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE, REALIZING THAT THE LEAK WOULD STOP AS SOON AS HE REACHED THE HALF WAY MARK. THIS ONLY TOOK A FEW MINUTES AND THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. ONLY A TRACE AMOUNT OF THE MATERIAL HAD LEAKED PRIOR TO FINISHING THE OFF LOADING.

column168: DURING SWITCHING STEX 13605 RELEASED LIQUID FROM THE 35 PSI SAFETY VALVE AND SPRAYED INTO A BNSF SWITCHMAN'S EYE. THE SWITCHMAN WAS DECONTAMINATED AND SENT TO THE HOSPITAL WERE THE EYES WAS FLUSHED AND EXAMINED. A PATCH WAS PUT ON THE EYE FOR 24 HOURS. THE EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO WORK THE NEXT DAY. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED AND AD APPROX. 20% OUTAGE. THE SAFETY VALVE WILL BE CHECKED BY TANK OWNER TO DETERMINE IF THE VALVE ID FUNCTIONING NORMALLY. AT THIS TIME, WE BELIEVE THAT THE HYDRAULIC PRESSURES GENERATED IN THE CAR DURING SWITCHING WERE IN EXCESS OF 35 PSI CAUSING LIQUID TO BE RELEASE OUT OF THE VALVE.

AT ARMSTRONG (THE NEXT STOP) THE BAG WAS DISCOVERED & ARMSTRONG EMPLOYEE WAS HELPING ASHLAND DRIVER RIGHT THE BAG.  IN DOING THIS HE HAD TO MOVE BAG ONTO THEIR DOCK WHICH UNBEKNOWN TO HIS WAS AGAINST ARMSTRONG POLICY.  THE EH&S MANAGER WOULD NOT LET ASHLAND DRIVER CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL SPILLED (<10 LBS).  EVEN THOUGH HE HAD THE PROPER PPE BECAUSE OF THE DUST GENERATED W/METALS.  CMI WAS CALLED IN THE CLEANUP WITH MATERIAL. DRIVER WENT ON HIS WAY.  GENERATOR WAS CONTACTED & NOW REALIZE BAGS WERE BEING FITTED TOO FULL & WAS GOING TO CHECK ON INTEGRITY OF BAGS.

INTERNAL DEFECT ON THE SAFETY VENT VALUE, GATX 12925, SEPTEMBER 15, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1555 HOURS, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 15, 1997, IN FRONTIER YARD, BUFFALO, NEW YORK, TWO CONRAIL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGERS NOTED VENTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 12925 CONTAINING CARBON DIOXIDE.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. GATX 12925 WAS INBOUND FROM INTERCHANGE AND WAS LOCATED ON THE INBOUND TRACK. CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGERS INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY VALVE WAS RELEASING PRODUCT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE CONSIGNEE, IRISH CARBONIC ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM IRISH CARBONIC OPENED THE VAPOR LINE AND ATTEMPTED TO RELIEVE PRESSURE ON THE CAR.  THIS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE SAFETY VALVE REMAINED IN THE OPENED POSITION.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO DELIVER THE CAR IMMEDIATELY TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING.  AFTER CONVERSATION, WITH THE LOCAL FRA INSPECTOR, IT WAS AGREED UPON THE CAR WOULD BE MOVED TO DESTINATION TO BE UNLOADED.  CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ACCOMPANIED THE TANK CAR TO DESTINATION.

HAZ MATERIAL KIT USED TO SEAL HOLE AND CLEAN UP RESIN.

DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING SULFURIC ACID FROM A MC-312 INTO A CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK.  IN THE PROCESS THE HOSE RUPTURED, AND WAS SPRAYING SULFURIC ACID.  THE DRIVER COULDN'T GET TO THE SHUT OFF VALVE ON THE TANK DO TO THE SPRAYING ACID.  THE DRIVER WAS USING CUSTOMER SUPPLY AIR TO PRESSURE OFF LOAD, HE HAD THE CUSTOMER SHUT THE AIR SUPPLY OFF.  THEY THEN HAD TO WAIT FOR THE TANK TO DE PRESSURIZE BEFORE THEY COULD GAIN ACCESS TO THE SHUT OFF VALVE ON THE TANK.  AFTER INVESTIGATING THE INCIDENT IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THEIR WAS A PREMATURE FAILURE OF THE HOSE.  WE HAVE NOW PURCHASED A BETTER GRADE OF HOSE AND ARE REVIEWING OUR HOSE PURCHASING PROCEDURES.  WE ARE ALSO REVIEWING THE TIME HOSES ARE IN SERVICE IN BETWEEN TESTING.

OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING EASTMAN FREIGHT AT HIS LAST STOP. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO OUR SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND ALSO TO EASTMAN. column168: PLEASE CONSIDER THIS CORRESPONDENCE AS WRITTEN CONFIRMATIONS A ONE (1) VEHICULAR ACCIDENT INVOLVING AN MC330 TRANSPORT OWNED AND OPERATED BY HERCULES TRANSPORT, INC. THE TRANSPORT WAS CARRY PG PROPANE AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER RIG OVERTURNED IN THE CURVE AT THE INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 42 & 11. AS IS NOTED IN THE POLICE REPORT, THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT HE SWERVED TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE CAUSING HIM TO LOOSE CONTROL OF THE TRANSPORT CAUSING THE ROLL OVER.  DIESEL FUEL FROM A RUPTURE OF THE TRACTOR FUEL TANK AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF ENGINE OIL WERE RELEASED TO THE ROAD SURFACE.  NO LPG PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DUE TO THE INCIDENT.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA SURROUNDING THE ACCIDENT SCENE WAS EVACUATED FROM 12 PM TO 9 PM.  DU FOUR PETROLEUM HAZMAT TEAM, MOBIL OIL'S HAZMAT TEAM, AND LOCAL & STATE RESPONDERS WERE THE FIRST TO RESPOND TO THE ACCIDENT.  HERCULES DIRECTOR OF MAINTENANCE AND CHIEF MECHANIC RESPONDED FROM THE BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA MAIN OFFICE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE OVERTURNED TRANSPORT CONTAINER WERE OFF-LOADED TO ANOTHER HERCULES TRANSPORT. AFTER COMPLETION OF THE OFF-LOADING OF THE CONTAINER THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE.  AT PRESENT, THE TRANSPORT CONTAINER IS BEING EVALUATED AT MISSISSIPPI TANK COMPANY, JACKSON, MISSISSIPPI.  A DECISION TO REPAIR THE CONTAINER TO ACTIVE SERVICE HAS NOT BEEN MADE AT THIS TIME.

THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND THERE WAS NO EFFECT ON ANY WATERWAY.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT REST AREA AND WHEN SHE DID A WALK-AROUND OF THE TRUCK, FOUND A DRIP COMING FROM THE CAP ON END OF DISCHARGE PIPE.  SHE PLACED A BUCKET AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE BUTLER COUNTY, ALABAMA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SENT PERSONNEL TO ISOLATE THE TANK TRUCK, CARRIER SENT A TRAINED TECHNICIAN LEVEL PERSON TO EVALUATE THE LEAK.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TANK TRUCK WAS NOT TOTALLY CLOSED, AND NEITHER WAS THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THIS PRODUCED PRESSURE IN UNLOADING LINE AND CAUSED THE CAP TO LEAK.  THE RESPONDER CLOSED ALL VALVES AND DRAINED THE LINE.  THERE WAS NO FURTHER EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  THE PRODUCT THAT HAD INTO BUCKET AND ALSO THAT WHICH WAS DRAINED FROM LINE WERE SEALED IN A CONTAINER AND TAKEN TO CARRIER'S ATLANTA, GA FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

DRIVER WAS ON TOP OF CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK CHECKING THE LEVEL WHEN THE HOSE BURST.  HE CAME DOWN FROM STORAGE TANK AND CLOSED VALUE ON TRAILER TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  NO MATERIAL REACHED WATERWAYS CUSTOMER PERSONNEL PERFORMED CLEANUP.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE UNLOADING SITE.

column168: DERAILMENT CAUSED BY IMPROPERLY LOADED COIL SHIELD CAR, DUNKIRK, NY, SEPTEMBER 15, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1930 HOURS, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 15, 1997, CONRAIL TRAIN ELBU5 DERAILED 36 CARS AT MILEPOST CP42 ON THE ALBANY LINE IN DUNKIRK, NY.  OUT OF THE 36 CARS THAT DERAILED THERE WERE 21 CARS THAT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS MADE.  THREE REPRESENTATIVES FROM CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT THE SITE.THE FOLLOWING IS A LIST OF THE 21 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS THAT DERAILED. ACFX 79293  CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, SPENT RELEASED PRODUCT ON SITE THROUGH A CRACK IN THE B-END HEAD SHIELD AND THE SAFETY VENT AFTER THE FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED.  EPS A CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  ESTIMATED RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS DETERMINED TO BE 5,300  LBS.  CAR WAS TRANSFERRED ON SITE BY EPS INTO THE FOLLOWING (3) TRAILERS: #4009 - 37,760 LBS, #4518 - 23,560 LBS, #4015 - 33,020 LBS.  A TOTAL 94,340 RECOVERED FROM TANK CAR AND DELIVERED TO PVS (C0NSIGNEE) FOR ACCEPTANCE.

DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PUMP  A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL FROM A CARGO TANK ON TO TANK CAR. DRIVER REVERSED THE HOSES TO THE PUMP,  RESULTING IN PRODUCT BEING PUMPED FROM THE TANK CAR INTO THE CARGO TANK, CAUSING THE CARGO TANK TO OVERFILL AND THE SUBSEQUENT RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROX. 2-3 OUNCES OF MATERIAL. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT THE ORGIN.

THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS SECURED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. column168: (A - B) AT 2400 HOURS, ON SEPTEMBER 7, 1997, A WILSONART 18 WHEELER WITH BOX TRAILER STRUCK A DEAD HORSE WHICH HAD ONLY MOMENTS BEFORE BEEN STRUCK DEAD BY AN ONCOMING VEHICLE. THE DRIVER COULD NOT CONTROL THE VEHICLE AFTER THE COLLISION AND OVERTURNED ON THE ROAD'S SHOULDER. THE IMPACT OF THE GROUND STRIKE AND THE WEIGHT OF SHIFTING CARGO CRUSHED THE VARIOUS PAILS OF ADHESIVE ON BOARD AND THEY BEGAN TO LEAK. THE DIESEL FUEL TANKS ALSO BEGAN TO LEAK. THE CITY OF FARMINGTON HAZ MAT TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY SUMMONED, AS WAS THE SHIPROCK POLICE DEPARTMENT, AND RILEY INDUSTRIAL SERVICES, A COMMERCIAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR. I HAVE NO RECOMMENDATIONS ON PREVENTION OF FUTURE ACCIDENTS, NOR ON IMPROVING THE PACKAGING, HANDLING, OR TRANSPORT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFESTS 94 0 ARE ATTACHED FOR MATERIAL GENERATED DURING SPILL. CONTINUED FROM #36 A SECOND PAIL SUPPLIER IS BROCKWAY STANDARD, ADDRESS IDENTICAL TO 36.B.

column168: SHIPPER PERSONNEL WERE BOTTOM LOADING A COMPARTMENT TRAILER.  AFTER LOADING COMPT #4, SHIPPER EMPLOYEE PROCEEDED TO OPEN COMPT #1 VALVE, UTILIZING THE HYDRAULIC SYSTEM, WHICH MALFUNCTIONED, CAUSING COMPT #4 TO ALSO OPEN, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO RUN OUT OF TRAILER.  CARRIER WAS NO INVOLVED IN RELEASE, BUT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE OCCURENCE BY THE SHIPPER.  CARRIER HAD A VALVE HYDRAULIC SYSTEM EXAMINED BY A MECHANIC. column168: OUR DRIVER, RICHARD A HOGLEN ARRIVED AT UNIROYAL CHEMICAL IN NAUGATUCK, CT AT 0700 HOURS ON 9/5/97 AND ASSISTED IN VACUUMING A LOAD OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (NONENES), 3.0 UN1993.  OUR DRIVER FINISHED LOADING AND DEPARTED THE GENERATORS FACILITY AT 1130 HOURS OF THE SAME DAY.  THE MATERIAL THAT WAS LOADED WAS ABOUT 150 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT DUE TO ITS VISCOUS NATURE WHEN THE MATERIALS TEMPERATURE DROPS BELOW 8 DEGREES.  OUR DRIVER MADE THE PERIODIC VEHICLE CHECKS AS REQUIRED BY THE DOT AND DID NOT DISCOVER ANY EQUIPMENT PROBLEMS WHILE ENROUTE.  AT 1530 HOURS, WHILE EXITING THE NEW JERSEY TURNPIKE AT EXIT #2 AND PAYING THE TOLL, OUR DRIVER NOTICED MATERIAL ON THE FRONT LEFT SIDE OF OUR VACUUM TANK TRAILER, V102T.  OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AT THE TURNPIKE, WHO THEN SPREAD SAND ON THE ROADWAY WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED.  OUR DRIVER PULLED INTO A LOT OFF TO THE SIDE AND UT OF THE FLOW OF TRAFFIC.  AT THIS TIME THE NOTIFIED MIKE DAILEY, THE TRANSPORTATION MANAGER AT LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE (BRIDGEPORT), INC.  MIKE DAILEY IN TURN NOTIFIED TERRY HARMESON, THE VICE PRESIDENT OF LES WHO IN TURN AUTHORIZED THE MANPOWER AND MATERIALS TO BE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST WITH CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES.

ON SEPTEMBER 9, `997, THE TRAIN CREW (WE 730) SAW VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANKCAR GATX14036, AND NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER.  JEFF CLAPPER RECEIVED A CALL AT 0615 HOURS FROM THE DISPATCHER STATING THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING TANK CAR.  ON ARRIVAL TO THE SCENE JEFF CLAPPER DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR WAS COMING FROM THE FRANGIBLE DISC.  JEFF REPLACED THE DISC ON THE CAR, AND INSPECTED IT.  AT 0920 HOURS THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED, THE SHIPPER WAS THEN NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED IN OUR SYSTEM.  BOTH ODOR AND APPROXIMATELY 2 LITERS OF A LIQUID SPILLED.  THE WET PACKAGE CONTAINED A STYROFOAM LAYER WITH A PART OF SOME SORT.  THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST SMELLED WHAT APPEARED TO BE KEROSENE OR JET FUEL.  THEY NOTIFIED THIS OFFICE AND I OBTAINED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (SEE ENCLOSED).  THE MSDS CLEARLY INDICATES THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF "FUEL AVIATION TURBINE ENGINE", UN 1863.  THE FLASH POINT IS 140 DEGREE FARENHEIT. SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  I NOTIFIED FAA AGENT SUE ANN ROBINSON AT (310) 215-2280 BY VOICE MAIL.  I RECEIVED A CALL BACK FROM FAA AGENT JUDY REASON WHO WILL BE DOING THE FAA'S INVESTIGATION OF THIS UNDECLARED FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE FEDEX LOCATION PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE OFFLOAD THE CYLINDER BEGAN LEAKING.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  I CONTACTED BOTH THE SHIPPER AND THE FAA.  THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD UNTIL THE FAA RELEASES IT.  I SPOKE WITH JIM STILLWELL FROM THE FAA.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED IN OUR SYSTEM.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT, IT APPEARED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY, "BATTERIES, WET - NONSPILLABLE" , UN2800.  AFTER PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE COMPLETED THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  I NOTIFIED F.A.A. AGENT JIM WEISMANN ON 9/17/1997 AT 310-725-3705 WHO INDICATED THAT FAA AGENT KATHLEEN ROSCHER WILL BE INVESTIGATING THIS INCIDENT.  THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT FEDEX PENDING THE F.AA. INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE OFFLOAD THE PACKAGES BEGAN EMITTING A STRONG ODOR.  UPON CLOSE EXAMINATION OF THE BOXES WE FOUND THAT THEY ALL WERE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL.  I HAD THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST PUT EACH BOX IN A HEAVY - MIL PLASTIC BAG AND HOLD THEM UNTIL I COULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER TODAY.  I SPOKE TO NANCY MAILLE.  NANCY SAID THAT THE DAMAGED WAS FEDEX'S FAULT.  I THEN ASKED HER IF SHE HAD ANY FORMAL DANGEROUS GOODS TRAINING OR IF THE BOXES HAD BEEN TESTED.  THE ANSWER TO BOTH INQUIRES WERE TO THE NEGATIVE.  I THEN NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT KATE ZAMPARELLI OF THE BOSTON FAA CASFO.  I ALSO SPOKE WITH LORI TINCKLEMAN WITH FMC.  AFTER FAA RELEASES THE FREIGHT FMC WILL SEND A TRUCK WITH ENOUGH SALVAGE DRUMS TO RECOVER THE FREIGHT.

column62: Water Damage; Defective Component or Device
column168: RECEIVED A CALL FROM MIKE FLYNN AT 1700 ABOUT A LEAKING HAZARDOUS AT PD-7 IN THE CHUTE AT 157 DOOR. HE IDENTIFIED THE PACKAGE AS CORROSIVE BY THE DIAMOND LABEL AND 5-PART FORM, AND STATED THAT IT WAS LEAKING IN THE CHUTE. RESPONDED TO PD-7 WEARING PROPER PPE AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE SHEETS. PLACED THE LEAKER IN A SPILL TUB, CLEANED UP SPILLAGE IN FEEDER AND CHUTE WITH SPEED DRY. PH TEST=0 NEUTRALIZED CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND PROCESSED THRU DMP PROGRAM.

THE EMPLOYEES UNLOADING THE CONTAINER OF FREIGHT NOTICED A STRONG ODOR. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS FOUND. AFTER THE PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED, THIS PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. SOME MATERIAL HAD GOTTEN ONTO AN EMPLOYEE WHO WENT TO THE DOCTOR. THE DOCTOR PHONED THE STATION REQUESTING THE MSDS. I CALLED THE SHIPPER AND HAD THE MSDS FAXED TO ME AND FORWARDED TO THE STATION TO GIVE TO THE DOCTOR. THE MSDS (SEE ENCLOSED) LISTED A FLASH POINT OF 100 DEGREES FARENHEIT CLOSED CUP. PER IATA STANDARDS THIS IS FLAMMABLE AS IT IS AT OR BELOW 141 DEGREES FARENHEIT CLOSED CUP. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT SENT AS DANGEROUS GOODS. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELINGS, OR PAPERWORK SENT WITH IT. THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY, "FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S", UN 1993, IN A PACKING GROUP III. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE FEDEX STATION PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. I NOTIFIED FAA HAZMAT COORDINATOR TOM KENNY AT (206) 227-1242. HE REQUESTED THAT I ALSO CALL FAA AGENT STEVE BRAISER AT (817) 222-5725. I LEFT A MESSAGE ON STEVE'S VOICE MAIL TO NOTIFY HIM OF THE INCIDENT.

LEONARD CHAMBERS (DRIVER OF DELTA DISTRIBUTORS, INC.) CHECKED WITH THE EMPLOYEES OF JONES STATION FOR THE UNLOADING OF THE SULFURIC ACID AND TO CHECK WITH SPS EMPLOYEES FOR TANK CAPACITIES. TANK SHOWED TO HAVE PLENTY AVAILABLE CAPACITY TO RECEIVE LOAD. AS LOAD WAS BEING DISCHARGED INTO TANK THE SULFURIC ACID OVER FLOWED FROM THE VENT PIPE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED FLOW LINE AND SHUT DOWN FLOW FROM TRUCK AND CONTACTED THE SPS PEOPLE. APPX. 10-15 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID SPILLED FROM STORAGE TANK. DRIVER FOLLOWED SP5 DIRECTIONS AND ASSISTED SPS PERSONNEL TO ALLOW OUR TRUCK TO BE MOVED. SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED ON SITE BY SP5 TEAM. DELTA DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM SITE. 240 POUNDS OF SULFURIC ACID  WAS LEFT ON OUR VEHICLE.

column168: ON 090897 CTS MGR. M. KELLY WAS NOTIFIED BY THE DENVER RMCC DESK THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING LIQUID PRODUCT FROM THE CABINET ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR. column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS WINNEMUCCA YARD, INSPECTED TANK CAR ACFX 94310, SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. NOTED BAND OF DRIED PRODUCT DOWN SIDE OF TANK CAR WITH POINT OF ORIGIN UNDERNEATH COMBINATION HOUSING COVER. REMOVED INTACT SEAL UPA 319360, OPENED COVER, AND NOTED LEAK WAS FROM DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. THERE WAS NO WAY TO REPAIR VALVE SO IT WAS REMOVED AND 1 1/2 INCH PIPE PLUG WAS INSTALLED TO MAKE TANK CAR LIQUID TIGHT. SEAL UPF 329859 WAS APPLIED TO COVER. NOTED HINGED MANWAY COVER LID PROTECTED SEAL UPA 319359 AND TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY PROTECTED SEAL UPA 319358. DON BURNS, SIERRA CHEMICAL, AND PHILLIP LUZMOVE, SOLVAY MINERALS, WERE ADVISED OF REMOVAL VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. CHEMTREC JOE BABER FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 59826.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY WAS NOTIFIED BY SPARKS YARDMASTER MILES THAT SWITCHMAN STEVE LAZZARI HAD BEEN SPLASHED BY SULFURIC ACID WHILE CREW WAS SWITCHING TANK CAR UTLX 12639 AT THE WEST END OF TRACK #15 SPARKS YARD. YARDMASTER MILES ADVISED THAT CAR WAS SHOWING AS RESIDUE EMPTY L/C SULFURIC ACID ON HIS YARD RECORDS. INSPECTION OF TANK CAR FOUND THAT THE FILL HOLE COVER GASKET WAS BROKEN AND IMPROPERLY APPLIED TO CLOSURE. PORTION OF GASKET WAS STICKING OUT FROM UNDER HINGED FILL HOLE COVER LID. ALSO NOTED PIPE PLUG LOCATED ON BALL VALVE AIR EDUCATION ASSEMBLY WAS FINGER TIGHT AND BALL VALVE WITHOUT OPERATING HANDLE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION. SAFETY VENT SPLASHED DEFLECTOR COVER WAS PROTECTED BY INTACT WIRE SEAL 40322 AND THIS WAS REMOVED TO INSPECT FRANGIBLE DISK, WHICH WAS NOTED INTACT. OPENED FILL HOLE COVER AND NOTED CAR TO BE A LOAD. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND CLOSURE SECURED WRENCH TIGHT. AIR VALVE ASSEMBLY WAS SECURED. HAD SWITCH CREW HANDLE TANK CAR TO ASSURE LEAK HAD BEEN SECURED. CONTACTED TUESDAY, KENNECOTT COPPER CORP. JAYHAWK, NV. WHO ADVISED THEIR RECORDS REFLECT CAR WAS UNLOADED ON 09/04/97. ADVISED HER OF CONDITION OF TANK CAR. CHEMTREC JOE BABER WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT #59880. SWITCHMAN LAZZRI WASHED IMPACTED AREAS WITH SOAP AND WATER AND RETURNED TO WORK.

REGIONAL MANAGER MIKE SEABAUGH WAS CONTACTED BY MECH. DEPT. FOREMAN MIKE MOORE AT UP SERVICE TRACK N. LITTLE ROCK YARD AND ADVISED THAT STRONG ODOR HAD BEEN DETECTED IN THAT AREA. INSPECTION REVEALED LEAKAGE FROM UNDER TOP UNLOADING PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. FOUR NUTS DESIGNED TO SECURE THREE INCH LIQUID VALVE TO THREE INCH SIPHON PIPE FLANGE  WERE FOUND LOOSE ALLOWING SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE BETWEEN FLANGE AND VALVE. ALSO THREE INCH PLUG LOCATED ON UNLOADING CONNECTION FLANGE WAS LOOSE. CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TO MAKE PLUG AND FLANGE "WRENCH TIGHT" WHICH SECURED TANK CAR AT 17:30 HOURS. MR. MIKE MOORE AND RMCC WERE ADVISED OF CORRECTIVE HANDLING.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, ERNIE SIROTEK WAS NOTIFED BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER, BEN PEDERSEN, AT 2039 HOURS, THAT THE LZW45-13 HAD DERAILED FOUR CARS INSIDE THE USS POSCO PLANT AT PITTSBURG, CA. THE A-END OF THE CAR WAS IN AN UPRIGHT CONDITION WITH A SLIGHT LIST TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR. THE PITTSBURGH POLICE DEPARTMENT SET UP AN INCIDENT COMMAND AND ORDERED A VOLUNTARY EVACUATION PENDING INSPECTION OF THE LOAD BY CONCORD NAVAL WEAPONS STATION PERSONNEL. THE EVACUATION WAS ORDERED AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 HOURS AND LIFTED AT APPROXIMATELY 2330 HOURS, AFTER THE LOAD HAD BEEN INSPECTED BY CONCORD NAVAL WEAPONS STATION PERSONNEL AND RAILROAD PERSONNEL. APPROXIMATELY 500-600 HOMES WERE IMPACTED BY THE EVACUATION ORDER. THE EVACUATION ORDER COVERED A 1/2 SQUARE MILE RADIUS OF THE INCIDENT. THE CAR WAS RERAILED AT 0430 HOURS ON 9/14/97. AFTER REPAIRS ARE MADE TO THE CAR BY UNION PACIFIC MECHANICAL FORCES, IT WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A STAIN AROUND THE MANWAY COVER. REEDER OPENED THE COVER AND FOUND ABOUT HALF OF THE GASKET WAS MISSING. UPTU 660210 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE ASSEMBLY AT THE MOUNTING FLANGE. ATTEMPTS TO SECURE FLANGE DID NOT STOP LEAKAGE, THEREBY NECESSITATING A TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT. MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, WAS ADVISED BY CHEYENNE CARMAN THAT HE NOTED A MTBE ODOR COMING FROM COASTAL CUT, SOUTH 6 TRACK, CHEYENNE, WY. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS BENT AND BAD ORDER. REMOVED VALVE AND PLUGGED, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. REMOVED SEAL: UP-A-49202, TO MAKE REPAIRS. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MGR. HARRY RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION OF A LEAKING CONTAINER FROM THE IDAHO CORRIDOR MANAGER. HE ADVISED THAT CONTAINER TMMU 448816 HAD BEEN SET OUT AT REVERSE, ID. WAITING REPAIR. HE ALSO ADVISED THAT THE STATE OF IDAHO, CHEMTREC, AND LOCAL RESPONSE AGENCIES HAD BEEN NOTIFIED. MGR. RODABOUGH CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, SIL MARTINEZ IN POCATELLO, AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO MEET HIM IN REVERSE. UPON ARRIVAL, MGR. RODABOUGH WAS MET BY REPRESENTATIVES OF THE IDAHO STATE POLICE HAZMAT TEAM, SA HAZMAT MARTINEZ, MTO, JERON PEAY, AND OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED TO A SIDE TRACK, WHERE REMEDIATION COULD TAKE PLACE. AT 0900 HRS. ON 9/25/97, WITH THE AID OF A PETIBONE CRANE AND A MANTIS CRANE, THE CONTAINER WAS SET ON THE GROUND AND OPENED. INSPECTION OF THE LOAD REVEALED LITTLE BLOCKING OR BRACING. THE LOAD CONSISTED OF 100-30 GALLONS BARRELS OF PRINTERS INK. THE SHIPPER HAD STACKED TWO PALLETS CONTAINING 10 DRUMS ON TOP OF THE EXISTING LOAD. ALL 10 DRUMS WERE ON THEIR SIDES AND HAD BEEN ROLLING AROUND ON TOP OF THE OTHER DRUMS. FOUR OF THE DRUMS WERE EMPTY AND FOUR MORE REQUIRED OVERPACKING. OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL EMPTIED AND CLEANED THE CONTAINER, OVERPACKED THE FOUR DRUMS AND RELOADED THE CONTAINER. THE LOAD WAS SECURED WITH SHRINK WRAP AND FOUR LOAD LOCK DEVICES. SECURITY SEAL #039802 WAS APPLIED AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT. MGR. RODABOUGH NOTIFIED CHEMTREC'S LEIF ERICKSON, WHO ASSIGNED CASE #60399. APL SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, LARRY WOFFORD WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR ALL COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE INCIDENT.

column168: AT 1330 HRS ON SUNDAY THE 28TH DAY OF SEPT MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR JAMES BOWEN, LEAD CARMEN AT THE ROPER YARD THAT TANK CAR NUMBER UTLX 12737 WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  HE ADVISED THAT THE TANK WAS LOCATED 16 FROM THE SOUTH ON TRACK 27 AWAITING REPAIR. MGR RODABAUGH INSPECTED TANK CAR UTLX12737 AND FOUND THE FILL HOLE GASKET TO ME MISAPPLIED ALSO, THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS BROKEN.  MGR RODABOUGH REAPPLIED THE GASKET AND SECURE IT.  THE BORKEN DISC, A BS&B 100 LBS, WAS COVER.  THE CAR WAS THEN WASHED WITH FIVE GALLON OF SODIUM BICARBONATE SOLUTION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE SPILLED IN OUR SYSTEM.  THE FEDEX DG/SPILL SPECIALIST OBTAINED THE MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE ORIGINAL MSDS (SEE ENCLOSED) WAS FOR SULFURIC ACID.  THUS SINCE THE SHIPMENT HAD NOT BEEN SHIPPED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, IT WAS REPORTED BY LOCAL ANCHORAGE OFFICE TO THE F.A.A. AGENT JEFF DIETZ, AS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  SINCE THAT TIME , I SPOKE WITH MIKE TARZALE AT HENRI SCHEIN WHO FAXED ME ADDITIONAL PAPERWORK AND AN MSDS THAT HE INDICATED WAS THE ACTUAL SOLUTION OF THE MIXTURE.  THIS NEW MSDS DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS. PREVIOUS TO HIM FAXING ME THIS INFORMATION I HAD GIVEN HIM THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION OFF THE LABEL ON THE SHIPMENT "769449259,831, 1E7, ID #553060 5017 - 605" SO HE COULD INVESTIGATED  AND SEND ME THE CORRECT MSDS ON THIS SOLUTION. column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS IN PRISTINE SHAPE.  WE FOUND THE MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL TWO ONE GALLON CANS.  THE CANS HAD CLIPS ON THEM BUT ONLY ONE CLIP WAS LEFT ON THE LEAKING CAN.  THE CANS WERE BAGGED IN THE BOX BUT EVEN THAT DID NOT STOP THE SPILL.  THE SHIPPER FAXED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS FOR THE TWO SEPARATE COMMODITIES.  THE MSDS REVEALED THAT THE SPILLED MATERIAL HAD A FLASHPOINT OF 130 DEGREES F.  THE SECOND MATERIAL THAT DID NOT SPILL HAD A FLASH POINT OF 120 DEGREES F. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS , OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  I SPOKE WITH LEE ADAMS AT THE SHIPPER.  THE FAA HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AND WE WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS IT WAS A PRODUCT WHICH SAID "FLAME RETARDENT", CLASS A FOR APPLICATION ON INTERIOR DOORS, CALLED FLAME NO MORE.  PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE COMPLETED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD UNTIL A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. (SEE ENCLOSED).  THE FLASH POINT IS LISTED AS 55 DEGREES CELCIUS, 131 DEGREES FARENHEIT.  THIS FLASH POINT FALLS UNDER THE DEFINITION OF A FLAMMABLE UNDER IATA WHICH INDICATES 60.5 DEGREES CELCIUS OR LESS AS FLAMMABLE.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR PACKAGING USED.  THUS, I BELIEVE IT TO BE UNDECLARED "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.", UN 1993.  I PHONED F.A.A. STEVE BRASCHER TO REPORT THIS AS WELL AS F.A.A. AGENT STEVE PEREZ.  WE ARE HOLDING THE SHIPMENT PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE F.A.A. AGENT ALTHEA MACK.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: THE FREIGHT WAS DESCRIBED AS MEDICAL INSTRUMENTS.  THE BOX IN QUESTION WAS BURIED UNDER THE OTHER BOXES ON THE SKID.  THE SHIPPER SHRINKWRAPPED THE SKID.  THE SPILL WAS FOUND AS WE WERE WEIGHING THE SKID FOR WEIGHT AND BALANCE.  AS MEDICAL INSTRUMENTS DO NOT LEAK AS A RULE, THE SKID WAS BROKEN DOWN.  THE LEAKING BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS: KODAK DEVELOPER.  I NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER & SPOKE TO TIM & RAYMOND WONG. BOTH SAID THAT THE FREIGHT ORIGINATED FROM THE DEFENSE DEPOT IN TRACY, CA.  I MADE SEVERAL ATTEMPTS TO OBTAIN AN MSDS FROM BOTH TRACY AND RAYMOND EXPRESS, ALL TO NBO AVAIL. ON 10/2/97, SPECIAL AGENT JENNETTE BEAN FROM THE FAA CASFO IN SFO CALLED ON ANOTHER MATTER.  FEELING THAT I HAD EXHUSTED ALL MEANS TO OBTAIN THE MSDS, I NOTIFIED JENNETTE OF OUR DILEMMA.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS MAY BE REGULATED.

THE FREIGHT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO FEDEX TO BE INSPECTED.  THE DRIVER HAD PARKED HIS TRUCK AT THE WAUKEGAN FEDEX STATION.  WHILE HE WAS DOING HIS PAPERWORK HE HEARD A LOUD EXPLOSION EMINATE FROM THE REAR OF THIS VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED FEDEX MGMT AND A HAZMAT TEAM EVENTUALLY ENTERED THE VEHICLE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM FOUND THE SHREDDED REMAINS OF A BIOHAZ PACKAGE THAT CONTAINED FIVE 5ML VIALS OF HUMAN SERUM. OUT INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT ABBOTT EMPLOYEE TOM SCHNEIDER HAD PACKED DRY ICE INTO THE PLASTIC JARS THAT CONTAINED THE SERUM.  THIS SERUM WAS LATER TESTED BY ABBOTT AND FOUND TO BE HEPATITIS C POSITIVE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ORIGINALLY DECLARED AS DRY ICE SHIPMENT, BUT NOT AS AN INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCE.  THE DAMAGE BOX WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  BOTH ABBOTT LABS & THE FAA WERE NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO ROM MASON FROM ABBOTT WHO TOLD US THRU MR. SCHNEIDER THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT INFECTIOUS, AND RAFAEL RAMOS, SPECIAL AGENT WITH THE ORD CASFO. ABBOTT HAS SINCE RECOVERED THE DAMAGED PACKAGE.  I HAVE ALSO FOLLOWED UP WITH AGENT RAMOS ON THE INFECTIOUS FINDING.  AGENT RAMOS PROCESSED TO FEDEX ON THE NIGHT OF THE INCIDENT AND INSPECTED THE FREIGHT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE INFECTIOUS.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OPERATOR LADD DRIVING A LOADED TRACTOR TRAILER RIG WAS WEST BOUND ON INTERSTATE #30 IN THE EARLY MORNING HOURS AND POSSIBLY WENT TO SLEEP AT THE WHEEL. THE RIG WAS IN THE LEFT HAND LANE AND STARTED TOWARD THE CENTER MEDIAN (NOTE: NO SKID MARKS FOUND) AND STRUCK A LONG SECTION OF GUARD RAILING. I FOUND 30' FROM THE START OF IMPACT 44' 5" LONG OF LIGHT TIRE MARKS ON THE 4' 3" WIDE CENTER SHOULDER 10 INCHES FROM THE EDGE. THE RIG TRAVELED 232' AND APPARENTLY RUPTURED THE LEFT SIDE FUEL TANK. THE RIG STARTED TO OVERTURN AND TRAVELED ANOTHER 66' BEFORE COMING TO REST ON IT'S LEFT SIDE IN THE MEDIAN UNDER THE RED LAKE ROAD OVERPASS. UPON COMING TO REST THE RIG CAUGHT FIRE AND BURNED. THE RIG AND CONTENTS WERE A TOTAL LOSS. IT IS NOTED ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER I FOUND THE WORD "DANGEROUS" IN THE TRIANGLE. THREE AREA VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENTS SENT TRUCKS TO THE SCENE TO HELP WITH THE FIRE. #1 FULTON, #2 PERRYTOWN, #3 A TRUCK FROM MILLER COUNTY.

THE RIG WAS IN THE LEFT HAND LANE AND STARTED TOWARD THE CENTER MEDIAN (NOTE: NO SKID MARKS FOUND) AND STRUCK A LONG SECTION OF GUARD RAILING. I FOUND 30' FROM THE START OF IMPACT 44' 5" LONG OF LIGHT TIRE MARKS ON THE 4' 3" WIDE CENTER SHOULDER 10 INCHES FROM THE EDGE. THE RIG TRAVELED 232' AND APPARENTLY RUPTURED THE LEFT SIDE FUEL TANK. THE RIG STARTED TO OVERTURN AND TRAVELED ANOTHER 66' BEFORE COMING TO REST ON IT'S LEFT SIDE IN THE MEDIAN UNDER THE RED LAKE ROAD OVERPASS. UPON COMING TO REST THE RIG CAUGHT FIRE AND BURNED. THE RIG AND CONTENTS WERE A TOTAL LOSS. IT IS NOTED ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER I FOUND THE WORD "DANGEROUS" IN THE TRIANGLE. THREE AREA VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENTS SENT TRUCKS TO THE SCENE TO HELP WITH THE FIRE. #1 FULTON, #2 PERRYTOWN, #3 A TRUCK FROM MILLER COUNTY.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: HEAVY FREIGHT WAS DISCOVERED LOADED ON TOP OF HAZMAT RESULTING IN A RELEASE.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED FOR TECHNICAL INFORMATION. TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT PADS.  SPENT PADS AND PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM WHICH IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS RESKIDDED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. LABELS, BUT FOUND NONE. TECHNICIAN FLORENCE THEN OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND NAIL POLISH GLITTER INSIDE. SHE VISUALLY INSPECTED EACH INNER DISPLAY CASE EACH CONTAINING 8 GLASS RECEPTACLES OF VARIOUS COLORS AND FOUND THAT ONLY 1 X 15 ML HAD BROKEN AND LEAKED OUT OF 96 TOTAL BOTTLES. TAKEN TO OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY AND PLACED INTO A SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM THEN PUT INTO OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY THE FAA. (B) ON OPERATIONS DATE 08/21/97, P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN DIANE RAMSDEN RESPONDED TO A CALL IN BUILDING K OF OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE ABOVE ABX AIR, INC ADDRESS. THE REPORT WAS OF A PACKAGE LEAKING AND HAD AN ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL TECHNICIAN RAMSDEN FOUND 4 BOXES THAT WERE BANDED TOGETHER AS ONE AND A PINK LIQUID WAS ESCAPING ONE CORNER OF THE PACKAGE. SHE VISUALLY INSPECTED ALL SIDES OF THE BOXES BUT DID NOT FIND ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS. SHE OPENED BOX #1 AND FOUND 1 OF 96 GLASS BOTTLES OF VARIOUS COLORS HAD BROKEN. SHE OPENED BOXES #2 AND #3 AND FOUND THAT 1 OF 96 ALSO HAD BROKEN IN EACH OF THESE BOXES. SHE OPENED BOX #4 AND FOUND 4 GLASS BOTTLES HAD BROKEN AND LEAKED THEIR CONTENTS. TECHNICIAN RAMSDEN BAGGED ALL FOUR BOXES INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND PUT THE SHIPMENT INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM. TECHNICIAN RAMSDEN THEN PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL IT COULD BE INVESTIGATED BY THE FAA.

column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THIS PACKAGE SPILLED IN OUR SYSTEM.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST, THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO HAVE SOME OUTLET PLUGS AS WELL AS AN AEROSOL CAN OF SPRAY PAINT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PACKAGED, MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANGEROUS GOODS BY THE SHIPPER.  AS I BELIEVED IT TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  I REPORTED IT TO THE FAA AGENT DON KENT AT 847-294-7685.  HE ASKED ME TO NOTIFY FAA AGENT PETER ARGEN AT 614-231-8056 WHICH I DID ON 9/23/97 AT 9:10 AM CENTRAL. ORIGINALLY, I ASSUMED THE SHIPPER WAS MUSEUM OF SCIENCE & TECHNOLOGY AS THAT WAS THE COMPANY NAME AND ADDRESS ON THE PACKAGE LISTED AS THE SHIPPER ADDRESS.  HOWEVER THE CONTACT NAME WAS BOB THOMAS.  WHEN I PHONED THE MUSEUM OF SCIENCE & TECHNOLOGY'S PERSONNEL DEPARTMENT THEY TOLD ME THAT THEY DID NO HAVE AN EMPLOYEE BY THAT NAME.  THEN I SPOKE WITH AN EMPLOYEE IN SHIPPING TIM HENDERSON, WHO TOLD ME THAT BOB THOMAS WORKS FOR BATELLE BUT WAS DOING SOME WORK AT THE MUSEUM ON THE DAY THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED.  ID DID RECEIVE A CALL FROM BOB THOMAS AT BATELLE SO THAT I COULD INFORM THEM OF THE INCIDENT AND COULD CONFIRM HIS CORRECT COMPANY ADDRESS.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON 9/25/97 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SUPERVISOR, TERRY CAIN REPORTED AN ODOR.  THE LOCATION WAS ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE BROWN AND SPILL TECHNICIANS, TAMMY FLORENCE AND  CARL HOHL RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE 2 METAL RECEPTACLES OF 1 GALLON CAPACITY EACH, BOTH RECEPTACLES LEAKED DUE TO CLOSURE FAILURE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 9/29/97 A SPILL WAS REPORTED WITH AN ODOR ON A FALCON AIRCRAFT LOCATED AT GATE B-14, ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SPILL TECHNICIAN, CHRIS CHAPPA RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL HE DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER BOX, IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 1 METAL RECEPTACLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THIS CLOSURE WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE METAL RECEPTACLE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN "RESIN, SOLUTION', WHICH IS FLAMMABLE.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT THAT LEAKED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS.  LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS ON HOLD PENDING INVESTIGATION AND RELEASE BY THE FAA.

ON 9/20/97 AT APPROXIMATELY 0015 HOURS, RANDY WILLIAMS/PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN OF ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY OF THE SAME ADDRESS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS A PROPERLY DECLARED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SHIPMENT OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (ISOPROPANOL.  IT WAS PACKED IN 2 X 4 LITRE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH FRICTION (SCREW-TYPE) CLOSURES, AND 2 X 1 LITRE GLASS RECEPTACLES WITH FRICTION (SCREW-TYPE) CLOSURES CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O,S.  (ETHYL METHYL KETONE, ETHYL ALCOHOL)  WHICH DID NOT LEAK, ALL PACKED IN ONE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE ISOPROPANOL APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM ONE OF THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH A LOOSE CLOSURE, FROM WHICH APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF PRODUCT LEAKED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO IT'S ORIGINAL DESTINATION.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THERE WERE OTHER PACKAGES LOADED ON TOP OF THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND THIS RESULTED IN THE TOP OF THAT PACKAGE BEING CRUSHED.  WHEN THE FREIGHT CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED THE CRUSHED BOX WAS TAKEN OUT OF THE CONTAINER. HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED SPILLAGE AND ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL VARIOUS FOOT CARE PRODUCTS.  AMONG THESE WERE SIX AEROSOL CANS OF A FLAMMABLE DISINFECTANT.  THE WEIGHT ON TOP IF THE PACKAGE CAUSED THE AEROSOLS TO INITIATE RELEASING APPROXIMATELY TEN OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: A/C ARRIVED IN SJD ON SEPT.11 WITH CAR BATTERY SPILL IN PIT NUMBER 2.  A NEW CAR BATTERY HAD BEEN INSIDE OF A PASSENGER'S DUFFEL BAG, ALONG WITH MOTOR OIL AND WE - 40.  IT WAS THE ONLY PIECE OF BAGGAGE IN THE PIT.  APPARENTLY, DURING TAKE OFF FROM THE LAX, THE BAGGAGE SLID TO THE BACK WALL OF THE PIT AND THE BATTERY TIPPED OVER SPILLING ITS CONTENTS.  THE ACID ATE THROUGH THE DUFFEL BAG AND WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE RAMP AGENT, THERE WAS A POOL (APPROX. 4" IN DIAMETER ) OF BATTERY ACID APPROX 4 INCHES IN DIAMETER ON THE REAR CENTER FLOOR OF THE PIT.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: ON MONDAY 9/27/97 AT APPROX. 3:45 AM BOBBY HALL IN TRACTOR #182243 WITH TRAILERS (FRONT) 27321 AND (REAR) 7622 WITH A 5000 LBS LIFT GATE.  THE FRONT TRAILER #27321 WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO PARAMOUNT POOL SUPPLY IN LAS VEGAS, TOTAL WEIGHT 20,254 PRODUCT LOADED WAS 144 CS OF 4/1 RETURNABLE HYDROCHLORIC ACID (4) 53 GAL DRUMS HYDROCHLORIC ACID, AND (18) 15 GAL DRUM OF HYPOCHLORIC ACID AND (2) TOTES CONTAINING 330 GAL OF HYPOCHLORIC SOLUTION BOTH TOTES WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO ANGELICA  IN NORTH LAS VEGAS, THE 2/1 PRODUCT WAS TO BE DEL TO (3) DIFFERENT LESLIE STORES.  JOHN BESSLER IN TRACTOR #182242 PULLING TRAILERS #27353 AND 7613 FULLY LOADED WITH APPROX 39,441 LBS.  BOTH BOBBY AND JOHN WAS NORTH BOUND ON HWY 15 SOUTH OF BARSTOW, CA AT APPROX 3:45 AM THEY PULLED OFF THE HWY AT LYNWOOD RD TO EAT AT DENNYS RESTAURANT.  AS THEY PULLED INTO THE PARKING LOT JOHN NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM TRAILER #7622. JOHN NOTIFIED BOBBY OF THE SITUATION AND THEY BOTH INVESTIGATED. BOBBY MOVED THE TRAILERS ONTO A SIDE ROAD WHICH WAS SLANTED (NORTH BEING THE HIGHEST POINT SOUTH BEING THE LOWEST POINT) ALLOWING THE LIQUID TO DRAIN FROM THE REAR TRAILER DOWN A ASPHALT CURB FOR APPROX 25 YARDS MADE A RIGHT TURN FOR APPROX 75 YARDS AN RUN OUT INTO THE DESERT APPROX 5O YDS FROM THE HWY.  AT APPROX. 4:10 AM I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM BOBBY HALL HE INFORMED ME THAT THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND THERE WAS NO PROBLEM AT THIS TIME.  I INSTRUCTED BOBBY TO STAY AT THE SAM LOCATION AND SEND JOHN TO MAKE HIS DELIVERIES.  AT APPROX 4:30 AM I CALLED MARCOS ROSALES (PROD MANAGER) AT HOME I REQUESTED TWO MEN FROM THE HAZMAT TEAM TO BRING A EMPTY TOTE TO BOBBY'S LOCATION AND TRANSFER THE PRODUCT.  I GOT DRESSED AND LEFT HOME FOR THE SCENE.  I ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROX 6:05 AM FOUND BOBBY HALL INSPECTED THE LEAKING TRAILER, WENT TO DENNYS RESTAURANT TO PLACE A CALL TO KAREN ADAMS AT THE INDUSTRY PLANT APPROX TIME 6:15 AM. FILLED KAREN IN ON THE SITUATION AND ASK HER TO NOTIFY ANDY WOODS OF THE SITUATION, SHE NOTIFIED ME THE HAZ MAT TEAM HAD OR WAS JUST LEAVING. AT APPROX 6:30 AM I RECEIVED A BEEPER CALL FROM KAREN I WENT TO DENNYS RESTAURANT TO PLACE A CALL ( THE CELL PHONE WAS NOT WORKING IN THIS AREA) KAREN STATED THAT ANDYS INSTRUCTIONS WAS TO DIKE THE RUN OFF AND CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT.  BOBBY AND I DIKED THE RUN OFF AND I WENT TO THE PHONE TO CALL THE FIRE DEPT.  THE POLICE DEPT WAS 1ST ON THE SCENE THEY BLOCKED OFF THE AREA AND ASKED FOR BOBBYS PAPER WORK, THE FIRE DPT WAS THERE SHORTLY AFTERWARDS.  THE FIRE DEPT WAS UNDER THE COMMAND OF LANCE MILANEZ DIVISION CHIEF.  AFTER THE POLICE AND THE FIRE DEPT CHECKED THE INVOICES THEY PUT ON PROPER BREATHING EQUIPMENT AND PROTECTIVE GEAR AND OPENED THE REAR DOOR.  AT THIS TIME THEY ALLOWED ME TO APPROACH THE TRAILER AND SHOW THEM WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM.  THEY PLACED EMPTY BUCKETS UNDER THE LEFT REAR OF THE TRAILER TO CATCH THE PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED DIRECT ON THE DAM TO REINFORCE THE DAM.  AT APPROX 8 AM THE U
column172: Composite, with plastic inner liner, for liquids

TANK CAR TEIX 20520 WAS PERPENDICULAR TO THE TRACK LEANING AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE EAST. PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. AT 1158 HRS ON 9-18-97 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS, EMG MGR KEELING IN COMPANY WITH FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR FRED BRYANT, NOTED TANK CAR BPOX 25013 TO BE LEAKING IN THE AREA OF THE MANWAY. THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO THE FREIGHTHOUSE TRACK UNTIL AN INSPECTION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. CTS MGR MARK REIMERS ARRIVED AT APPROX. 1600 HRS AND ESTABLISHED THAT THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF A CRACKED MANWAY GASKET. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. JOANNE KENNY OF NALCO WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF REPAIRS. SHE WAS FURTHER ADVISED THAT A PERMANENT GASKET WOULD NEED TO BE INSTALLED PRIOR TO RELOADING OF THE TANK CAR.

BAY WEST ARRIVED AT 2130 AND SECURED AREA. HAZARDOUS PRO 203-926100, 2 DRUMS, 1100 LBS, WERE REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND PLACED IN RECOVERY CONTAINERS.  ONE DRUM HAD A LEAKY LOWER SEAL. ON 9-26-97 SORT SUPERVISOR, NANCY CURL REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND PART-TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, CHRIS CHAPPA RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED.  PART-TIME TECHNICIAN CHAPPA DONNED A ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. INSIDE WERE TWO METAL RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THESE DID HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THESE WERE NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.
